## Choosing Your Shield

### By Guard Bonus

**+1 Guard (Buckler, Small Shield):**
Minimal protection but also minimal restriction. Bucklers uniquely strap to your forearm, allowing them to be used even while wielding two-handed weapons—the only shield with this capability. Small shields provide standard +1 Guard while held. Both suit characters who want modest defense without committing fully to shield use.

**+2 Guard (Medium Shield, Large Shield):**
Standard defensive options for frontline fighters. Medium shields provide the +2 Guard without special restrictions. Large shields grant the same +2 Guard plus the ability to use your shield as cover against ranged attacks—crouch behind it for additional protection from arrows and spells. Most shield-using characters choose this tier.

**+3 Guard (Tower Shield):**
Maximum protection at significant cost. The tower shield's massive size makes you substantially harder to hit (+3 Guard) but the weight and bulk impose -1 to all attack rolls. Only dedicated defensive characters should use tower shields—the attack penalty matters less when your job is surviving, not killing.

### By Character Type

**Fighters** typically use medium or large shields. The +2 Guard significantly improves frontline survivability without the attack penalty of tower shields. Pair with medium weapons for balanced offense and defense.

**Paladins** can effectively use any shield type, including tower shields. Heavy armor already makes you slow; the tower shield's attack penalty matters less when your role is protecting allies rather than dealing damage. Large shields provide excellent balance.

**Rangers** rarely use shields beyond bucklers. Your light armor and ranged focus prioritize mobility over defense. If you must use a shield, bucklers maintain the most freedom of movement.

**Rogues** occasionally use small shields when expecting combat, but typically avoid shields entirely. Grace-based defense and positioning matter more than passive Guard bonuses, and shields interfere with climbing, stealth, and two-weapon fighting.

**Spellcasters** rarely use shields. Wizards almost never do—they use Mage Armor instead. Clerics might use small or medium shields when expecting melee, balancing spellcasting needs with frontline presence. Bards avoid shields to preserve casting and mobility.

### Shield Tactics

**With Defensive Stance:**
Shield bonuses stack with stance bonuses. Medium shield (+2) plus Defensive stance (+2) equals +4 Guard total. Combined with armor DR, this makes you extremely difficult to damage. Frontline defenders in Defensive stance with shields become nearly untouchable walls.

**Two-Handed Weapons vs. Shield:**
Two-handed weapons deliver higher base damage (2d6+2 vs 2d6+1). Shields provide significant Guard bonuses (+1 to +3). The choice: kill enemies faster versus survive their attacks longer. Most frontline characters prefer shields—staying alive matters more than maximum damage.

**Buckler Special Case:**
Bucklers uniquely work with two-handed weapons. Strap a buckler to your arm, wield your greatsword with both hands, gain +1 Guard. You sacrifice the shield slot for modest protection, but it's better than nothing for two-handed weapon specialists who want some defense.

**Shield as Cover:**
Large shields provide cover against ranged attacks. When facing archers or spellcasters, you can crouch behind your shield for additional protection. This matters more in ranged-heavy encounters and makes large shields particularly valuable against magic-using enemies.

